`template/` is the scaffold generated for new Rust projects built by this repo's tooling: a workspace manifest plus a stacked, intentionally redundant lint/format/dependency policy, CI wiring, and Claude Code integration, all shipped as static config to be copied into a fresh project.

The policy stack spans several files and must stay internally consistent: `Cargo.toml` declares workspace-level clippy/rustc lints (deny warnings, unsafe, unwrap/expect/panic, etc.) that are inert unless each member crate opts in via `[lints]\nworkspace = true`, which `scripts/workspace_lints_check.sh` verifies. `clippy.toml` sets hard-fail thresholds (80 lines, complexity 25) but the tighter soft-tier thresholds referenced in its own edit_notes (30 lines, complexity 15) live only in `scripts/rationale_check.py` and an undocumented dylint crate — changing one without the other breaks the documented tiering. `rust-toolchain.toml` pins the compiler version that `rustfmt.toml` and `clippy.toml` both assume; bumping the toolchain requires re-verifying rustfmt's "stable-only options" claim and re-running clippy's full lint list, since lint names can shift across releases. `deny.toml` is the independent axis (licenses, registries, dependency duplication) not covered by clippy or rustc lints at all.

`.gitattributes` names a `ctx-regenerate` merge driver for `.ctx`/`rollup.ctx` files that does not yet exist as an actual git config entry — conflicts in generated context files currently require manual `ctx-resummarize` rather than automatic resolution. `.claude/settings.json` triggers `ctx-context --hook` on read-only tool use against a debug build path, silently no-opping if unbuilt; `.github/` wires CI to `scripts/ci.sh`, which in turn calls the `scripts/` check scripts as gates — those scripts share a "never silently pass" posture (missing tools are hard failures, not skips) and a common file-enumeration convention via `git ls-files` to avoid racing `target/` writes.

No intent.md exists to check divergence against.